1
00:00:10,575 --> 00:00:13,100
[car horns honking in distance]

2
00:00:13,143 --> 00:00:15,189
[bell jingles]

3
00:00:15,232 --> 00:00:18,409
Richard. Richard Briggs.

4
00:00:20,585 --> 00:00:22,370
This is for Ella.

5
00:00:23,240 --> 00:00:24,894
[people screaming, dog barking]

6
00:00:27,679 --> 00:00:29,464
[panting]

7
00:00:30,247 --> 00:00:32,249
[sirens wailing]

8
00:00:34,904 --> 00:00:36,384
CHUNK:
Fruit again?

9
00:00:36,427 --> 00:00:37,602
You know,

10
00:00:37,646 --> 00:00:39,430
those come from trees.

11
00:00:39,474 --> 00:00:41,258
Trees live in dirt.

12
00:00:41,302 --> 00:00:44,131
You want to give the boss food
that comes from dirt, go ahead.

13
00:00:44,174 --> 00:00:46,002
But honestly, I think at this
point, the man would appreciate

14
00:00:46,046 --> 00:00:47,569
coffee and a doughnut.

15
00:00:47,612 --> 00:00:49,005
Not funny.

16
00:00:49,049 --> 00:00:50,963
I know I would appreciate
coffee and a doughnut.

17
00:00:51,007 --> 00:00:53,096
I mean, look at this stuff.

18
00:00:53,140 --> 00:00:54,706
Quinoa porridge?

19
00:00:54,750 --> 00:00:57,361
Look, I'm all for healthy,
but this stuff will kill you.

20
00:00:57,405 --> 00:00:59,668
You got any food around here
for real people?

21
00:00:59,711 --> 00:01:02,671
Top drawer on your left,
behind the paper towels.

22
00:01:02,714 --> 00:01:04,325
Don't tell anyone.

23
00:01:04,368 --> 00:01:05,674
Don't tell anyone what?

24
00:01:05,717 --> 00:01:09,112
Hallelujah. Mmm.

25
00:01:15,292 --> 00:01:17,468
[sighs]

26
00:01:20,384 --> 00:01:22,778
Damn, I miss her.

27
00:01:22,821 --> 00:01:28,044
Her mom keeps promising to come
by and pick up her things.

28
00:01:28,088 --> 00:01:30,307
I'll make sure
and add that to the box.

29
00:01:32,527 --> 00:01:34,311
Anybody hear about that guy who
was gunned down on the sidewalk

30
00:01:34,355 --> 00:01:37,140
in the middle of the day
during a beer run yesterday?

31
00:01:37,184 --> 00:01:38,141
That poor woman.

32
00:01:38,185 --> 00:01:39,708
That poor man.

33
00:01:39,751 --> 00:01:41,971
It happened right around
the corner from where I live.

34
00:01:42,014 --> 00:01:44,582
She just walked up to him,
shot him, point blank range.

35
00:01:44,626 --> 00:01:46,758
Well, no. She didn't just.

36
00:01:46,802 --> 00:01:48,586
The guy raped and killed
her daughter.

37
00:01:48,630 --> 00:01:50,501
And believe me, if something
like that ever happens

38
00:01:50,545 --> 00:01:53,548
to my child, I'm gonna want
to do the exact same thing.

39
00:01:53,591 --> 00:01:56,507
Well, wanting is fine.
Doing is a whole other thing.

40
00:01:56,551 --> 00:01:58,509
There are laws in this country.

41
00:01:58,553 --> 00:02:00,381
Yeah, well, obviously
the law didn't work

42
00:02:00,424 --> 00:02:02,513
for the woman
who lost her daughter.

43
00:02:02,557 --> 00:02:04,298
I mean, she was just doing
what the jury refused to do.

44
00:02:04,341 --> 00:02:06,996
Oh, you can't blame the jury.

45
00:02:07,039 --> 00:02:09,346
They were never given the
evidence they needed to convict.

46
00:02:09,390 --> 00:02:11,218
How is that even possible?

47
00:02:11,261 --> 00:02:12,958
I mean, they found
the girl's body

48
00:02:13,002 --> 00:02:14,308
in the trunk
of this guy's car.

49
00:02:14,351 --> 00:02:15,613
What more do you need?

50
00:02:15,657 --> 00:02:17,615
Problem is, the jury
never heard any of that.

51
00:02:17,659 --> 00:02:20,444
Turns out, the police had

52
00:02:20,488 --> 00:02:23,099
a description
of the kidnapper's car.

53
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:26,276
Now, this Richard Briggs was
driving a car that matched,

54
00:02:26,320 --> 00:02:28,626
so the police pulled him over
and they searched it.

55
00:02:28,670 --> 00:02:32,152
Now, if there were a body
laying in the back seat,

56
00:02:32,195 --> 00:02:33,544
wouldn't have been a problem.

57
00:02:33,588 --> 00:02:34,719
But it was in the trunk.

58
00:02:34,763 --> 00:02:37,505
And you're not allowed
to open the trunk

59
00:02:37,548 --> 00:02:39,376
without probable cause.

60
00:02:39,420 --> 00:02:42,292
At that point
the police didn't have it.

61
00:02:42,336 --> 00:02:43,554
BULL:
Marissa!

62
00:02:45,034 --> 00:02:47,384
You barked, sir?

63
00:02:47,428 --> 00:02:49,647
How long has this piece of mail
been sitting on my desk?

64
00:02:49,691 --> 00:02:52,172
Your jury summons? Since April.

65
00:02:52,215 --> 00:02:54,522
Oh. Really? Six months.

66
00:02:54,565 --> 00:02:56,480
That postmark in the upper
right-hand corner?

67
00:02:56,524 --> 00:02:57,699
That is a dead giveaway.

68
00:02:57,742 --> 00:02:59,570
Well, make a call
and get me out of it.

69
00:02:59,614 --> 00:03:01,703
You know I can't do that.
We've already postponed it once,

70
00:03:01,746 --> 00:03:03,313
and that's all you're allowed.

71
00:03:03,357 --> 00:03:05,228
When are you due to report?

72
00:03:05,272 --> 00:03:06,795
Day after tomorrow.

73
00:03:06,838 --> 00:03:08,231
Damn it, what a waste of time.

74
00:03:08,275 --> 00:03:09,885
I spend half a day waiting
to be interviewed,

75
00:03:09,928 --> 00:03:11,626
and then the attorneys
figure out who I am,

76
00:03:11,669 --> 00:03:13,541
and they can't
get rid of me fast enough.

77
00:03:13,584 --> 00:03:14,846
It's not easy being you.

78
00:03:14,890 --> 00:03:16,631
And another thing:
my phone is not working.

79
00:03:16,674 --> 00:03:18,067
It hasn't rung in days.

80
00:03:18,110 --> 00:03:19,199
The phones are fine.
They're not ringing

81
00:03:19,242 --> 00:03:20,243
because no one's calling.

82
00:03:20,287 --> 00:03:21,462
What do you mean?

83
00:03:21,505 --> 00:03:24,291
You haven't been here
for three months.

84
00:03:24,334 --> 00:03:26,249
I mean, let's be honest.

85
00:03:26,293 --> 00:03:27,946
You're the reason people call.

86
00:03:27,990 --> 00:03:29,383
And they called plenty
while you were away,

87
00:03:29,426 --> 00:03:31,036
but after a while,
people get tired of hearing,

88
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:33,038
"He's not here and we're
not certain when he'll be back."

89
00:03:33,082 --> 00:03:34,301
Hmm.

90
00:03:34,344 --> 00:03:36,259
Well, I guess
we need to make some noise.

91
00:03:36,303 --> 00:03:37,652
Let people know
we're back up to speed.

92
00:03:37,695 --> 00:03:39,088
Call over to the D.A.'s office.

93
00:03:39,131 --> 00:03:41,438
See if there's any juicy
pro bono opportunities

94
00:03:41,482 --> 00:03:42,874
we can avail
ourselves of.

95
00:03:42,918 --> 00:03:45,094
Something that will
get us some clicks,

96
00:03:45,137 --> 00:03:46,835
some ink, some TV time.

97
00:03:46,878 --> 00:03:49,011
Clicks, ink, and TV time.

98
00:03:49,054 --> 00:03:50,273
I love it
when your better angels make

99
00:03:50,317 --> 00:03:52,144
an unscheduled cameo appearance.

100
00:03:53,885 --> 00:03:55,887
You know what?

101
00:03:57,062 --> 00:04:00,283
I think I might actually
have something for you.

102
00:04:00,327 --> 00:04:04,374
He'd come over every Wednesday.

103
00:04:04,418 --> 00:04:07,508
Always commenting
on how they looked.

104
00:04:07,551 --> 00:04:10,946
Their clothes,
their hair, how...

105
00:04:10,989 --> 00:04:14,950
how beautiful they were.

106
00:04:14,993 --> 00:04:17,866
He was your daughter's
piano teacher.

107
00:04:17,909 --> 00:04:21,522
I always thought it was
about the 15-year-old.

108
00:04:23,350 --> 00:04:28,746
When I... think about
the things he did

109
00:04:28,790 --> 00:04:31,662
to my little one.

110
00:04:31,706 --> 00:04:33,664
To Ella.

111
00:04:33,708 --> 00:04:37,451
And then,
suddenly he was free.

112
00:04:37,494 --> 00:04:39,540
It was like
it never happened.

113
00:04:39,583 --> 00:04:41,019
I'd lost my 11-year-old,

114
00:04:41,063 --> 00:04:44,240
and he was driving around town
like it was a holiday.

115
00:04:44,284 --> 00:04:47,243
Like he'd gotten away
with murder.

116
00:04:47,287 --> 00:04:49,811
Which he had.

117
00:04:49,854 --> 00:04:52,640
So I went and bought a gun.

118
00:04:52,683 --> 00:04:55,251
Something I thought
I'd never do.

119
00:04:55,295 --> 00:04:58,036
Easiest thing in the world.

120
00:04:58,080 --> 00:05:01,431
And then I just waited for him.

121
00:05:01,475 --> 00:05:04,652
So you shot him three times
in the chest in broad daylight

122
00:05:04,695 --> 00:05:07,045
in front of a dozen witnesses.

123
00:05:07,089 --> 00:05:09,439
And didn't even try to flee.

124
00:05:09,483 --> 00:05:11,702
You must have known you weren't
gonna get away with it.

125
00:05:11,746 --> 00:05:13,661
I didn't care.

126
00:05:13,704 --> 00:05:17,317
I wasn't thinking
about any of that.

127
00:05:19,493 --> 00:05:24,149
I just needed to know
he was no longer among us.

128
00:05:26,717 --> 00:05:28,719
♪

129
00:05:39,469 --> 00:05:40,557
[excited chatter]

130
00:05:40,601 --> 00:05:42,559
Just keep your head down
and ignore them.

131
00:05:42,603 --> 00:05:44,474
So what happens today?

132
00:05:44,518 --> 00:05:47,042
A number of things, but first
off, there's a question of bail.

133
00:05:47,085 --> 00:05:49,305
Oh, my gosh, you think they'll
actually offer me bail?

134
00:05:49,349 --> 00:05:52,134
No, but we have to go through
the formality of asking.

135
00:05:52,177 --> 00:05:54,092
And then the other side gets to
indulge in the sadistic pleasure

136
00:05:54,136 --> 00:05:56,094
of telling the court what
a dangerous person you are.

137
00:05:56,138 --> 00:05:57,792
It's just part of the fun.

138
00:05:57,835 --> 00:05:59,228
[quietly]:
Look at me, Mrs. Spiro.

139
00:05:59,271 --> 00:06:02,231
We're gonna get you
through this,

140
00:06:02,274 --> 00:06:04,059
and then we're gonna
get you out of here.

141
00:06:04,102 --> 00:06:06,453
You just have to trust me.

142
00:06:06,496 --> 00:06:08,280
Earth to Marissa.

143
00:06:08,324 --> 00:06:10,108
Benny and I and our client
are making our way

144
00:06:10,152 --> 00:06:11,153
into the courtroom.

145
00:06:11,196 --> 00:06:13,068
Bull, what are you
talking about?

146
00:06:13,111 --> 00:06:15,070
You have jury duty this morning.

147
00:06:15,113 --> 00:06:17,072
[sighs]

148
00:06:17,115 --> 00:06:18,639
You're gonna need this.

149
00:06:18,682 --> 00:06:19,857
You all right?

150
00:06:19,901 --> 00:06:21,206
No, I think I may
have screwed up.

151
00:06:21,250 --> 00:06:23,078
I have a bit of business
I need to take care of.

152
00:06:23,121 --> 00:06:24,471
Mrs. Spiro,

153
00:06:24,514 --> 00:06:25,907
I have to run upstairs
to another courtroom

154
00:06:25,950 --> 00:06:27,169
for a couple of hours.

155
00:06:27,212 --> 00:06:28,736
A couple of hours?It's not a problem.

156
00:06:28,779 --> 00:06:30,564
Nothing of any consequence
ever happens here before lunch,

157
00:06:30,607 --> 00:06:31,739
and even if it did,

158
00:06:31,782 --> 00:06:33,175
you couldn't be in better hands.

159
00:06:33,218 --> 00:06:34,655
You got it.

160
00:06:34,698 --> 00:06:36,178
Mrs. Spiro?

161
00:06:36,221 --> 00:06:37,179
Bull?

162
00:06:37,222 --> 00:06:38,310
How late am I?

163
00:06:38,354 --> 00:06:39,964
20 minutes.

164
00:06:40,008 --> 00:06:42,184
How long do you think
it'll take me to get excused?

165
00:06:42,227 --> 00:06:44,404
I have no idea
what you're talking about.

166
00:06:44,447 --> 00:06:47,407
I'm betting 45 minutes.

167
00:06:50,235 --> 00:06:52,977
A.A.G. LANFORD:
The defendant,

168
00:06:53,021 --> 00:06:58,418
one Kendrick Gorman,
who is accused

169
00:06:58,461 --> 00:07:00,724
of practicing law

170
00:07:00,768 --> 00:07:04,467
without a license.

171
00:07:04,511 --> 00:07:06,251
BULL: My God, he's actually
pronouncing every comma.

172
00:07:06,295 --> 00:07:08,297
That's right.

173
00:07:08,340 --> 00:07:12,214
Could there possibly be
a bigger abuse of trust?

174
00:07:13,476 --> 00:07:17,045
You find yourself
on the wrong side of the law.

175
00:07:17,088 --> 00:07:18,699
Desperate for help.

176
00:07:18,742 --> 00:07:20,570
You hire an attorney.

177
00:07:20,614 --> 00:07:24,356
Only to find that he's not
really an attorney.

178
00:07:24,400 --> 00:07:29,536
But an impostor.

179
00:07:29,579 --> 00:07:32,060
BULL: As opposed to an authentic idiot like you.

180
00:07:32,103 --> 00:07:35,237
Dr. Jason Bull.

181
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:38,196
TheDr. Jason Bull?

182
00:07:38,240 --> 00:07:39,981
Hmm. I'm afraid so.

183
00:07:40,024 --> 00:07:42,113
What a pleasure
to finally meet you.

184
00:07:42,157 --> 00:07:44,028
And you, as well.

185
00:07:44,072 --> 00:07:46,770
And now, I know you've done work
with my office,

186
00:07:46,814 --> 00:07:50,165
the state attorney
general's office, and I know

187
00:07:50,208 --> 00:07:53,037
you're also thought to be
one of the best in your field.

188
00:07:53,081 --> 00:07:55,475
So, just to be clear,
you advise

189
00:07:55,518 --> 00:07:59,000
people like me
how to pick juries.

190
00:07:59,043 --> 00:08:03,004
What to say to juries,
how to get the juries to come

191
00:08:03,047 --> 00:08:06,703
to conclusions whoever hires you
needs them to come to.

192
00:08:06,747 --> 00:08:07,965
Is that correct?

193
00:08:08,009 --> 00:08:10,490
Well, that's not
how I'd put it, but...

194
00:08:10,533 --> 00:08:13,188
Your Honor, we'd like
to strike this juror for cause.

195
00:08:13,231 --> 00:08:14,624
What cause?

196
00:08:14,668 --> 00:08:16,365
Well, you just heard him.

197
00:08:16,408 --> 00:08:18,367
He is an expert

198
00:08:18,410 --> 00:08:20,543
in all matters
pertaining to juries.

199
00:08:20,587 --> 00:08:22,153
HUDSON:
And that's all well and good.

200
00:08:22,197 --> 00:08:25,548
But as far as I can tell,
in this particular case,

201
00:08:25,592 --> 00:08:28,682
Dr. Bull will not
be picking jurors.

202
00:08:28,725 --> 00:08:31,336
Nor will he be advising either
side on what to say to them.

203
00:08:31,380 --> 00:08:34,209
And as far as helping them
come to conclusions,

204
00:08:34,252 --> 00:08:35,558
well, hopefully that's the job

205
00:08:35,602 --> 00:08:39,344
of every juror during
the period of deliberations.

206
00:08:39,388 --> 00:08:42,130
Ms. Dunn, would you care
to question the juror?

207
00:08:44,567 --> 00:08:47,178
So you're a jury consultant?

208
00:08:47,222 --> 00:08:49,180
A trial scientist, yes.

209
00:08:49,224 --> 00:08:52,270
You advise lawyers
on how to try their cases.

210
00:08:52,314 --> 00:08:54,708
Sometimes, yes.

211
00:08:54,751 --> 00:08:58,712
So, in a sense, you practice law
without a license.

212
00:08:58,755 --> 00:09:00,235
Just like my client.

213
00:09:00,278 --> 00:09:02,411
No, I wouldn't exactly say that.

214
00:09:02,454 --> 00:09:04,892
This juror
is acceptable to the defense.

215
00:09:04,935 --> 00:09:07,808
Your Honor, uh, if I may,

216
00:09:07,851 --> 00:09:10,332
I would love
to be seated on this jury.

217
00:09:10,375 --> 00:09:12,769
Well, then, today's
your lucky day.

218
00:09:12,813 --> 00:09:14,423
But unfortunately, um,

219
00:09:14,466 --> 00:09:17,948
I have a-a previous commitment,
a legal commitment.

220
00:09:17,992 --> 00:09:19,471
A legal commitment?

221
00:09:19,515 --> 00:09:22,387
Yes, indeed. Uh, I am
in the midst of starting

222
00:09:22,431 --> 00:09:25,869
a murder trial downstairs,
right in this very courthouse.

223
00:09:25,913 --> 00:09:29,264
And, um... uh,
you may have heard of it.

224
00:09:29,307 --> 00:09:31,658
The State v. Heather Spiro?

225
00:09:31,701 --> 00:09:34,138
It's a very big, important case.

226
00:09:34,182 --> 00:09:36,097
Yes, I have heard of it.

227
00:09:36,140 --> 00:09:37,925
Well, aren't you the VIP?

228
00:09:37,968 --> 00:09:39,013
[chuckles]

229
00:09:39,056 --> 00:09:40,841
However, trial scientists
are not now,

230
00:09:40,884 --> 00:09:42,930
nor have they ever been,
essential

231
00:09:42,973 --> 00:09:45,454
to the American
criminal justice system.

232
00:09:45,497 --> 00:09:47,630
But jurors are.

233
00:09:47,674 --> 00:09:50,198
Your Honor, my client
is facing a life sentence.

234
00:09:50,241 --> 00:09:51,373
She has a lawyer?

235
00:09:51,416 --> 00:09:53,636
She does.

236
00:09:53,680 --> 00:09:56,770
Good. Then everybody has
what they need.

237
00:09:56,813 --> 00:09:59,337
She has a lawyer,
we have 12 jurors.

238
00:09:59,381 --> 00:10:02,123
Welcome to my court, Dr. Bull.

239
00:10:02,166 --> 00:10:04,952
And welcome to jury duty.

240
00:10:11,523 --> 00:10:14,701
Ah. You can win
$100 million verdicts

241
00:10:14,744 --> 00:10:16,528
against multinational
corporations,

242
00:10:16,572 --> 00:10:18,792
but you can't argue
your way out of jury duty?

243
00:10:18,835 --> 00:10:20,402
Trust me, I tried.

244
00:10:20,445 --> 00:10:22,056
I think the judge
has a crush on me.

245
00:10:22,099 --> 00:10:23,013
Needless to say,

246
00:10:23,057 --> 00:10:24,972
our client is not pleased.

247
00:10:25,015 --> 00:10:26,016
Oh, I don't blame her.

248
00:10:26,060 --> 00:10:27,801
You just missed her.

249
00:10:27,844 --> 00:10:30,020
They just put her in
the prison van ten minutes ago.

250
00:10:30,064 --> 00:10:33,763
Well, the good news is, I won't
be on this jury for long.

251
00:10:33,807 --> 00:10:35,809
There are only three people
on the witness list.

252
00:10:35,852 --> 00:10:37,811
Whole thing should
be over in a day.

253
00:10:37,854 --> 00:10:39,900
Now, I was thinking
for tomorrow,

254
00:10:39,943 --> 00:10:42,076
it makes sense to promote Chunk
to the second chair.

255
00:10:42,119 --> 00:10:44,078
Someone sitting next to you
with Marissa in his ear.

256
00:10:44,121 --> 00:10:46,907
I get that.
So what's the strategy?

257
00:10:46,950 --> 00:10:48,909
Well, I'm thinking
EED defense.

