512
00:21:53,616 --> 00:21:54,922
I have got a trial
to prepare for.

513
00:21:59,535 --> 00:22:01,494
Well, I guess we're done here.

514
00:22:07,282 --> 00:22:08,718
BULL:
Don't speak.

515
00:22:08,762 --> 00:22:10,764
Three things.

516
00:22:10,807 --> 00:22:13,854
First thing, I don't give a damn
who you're pissed off at or why.

517
00:22:13,897 --> 00:22:15,246
When you're sitting
in that courtroom,

518
00:22:15,290 --> 00:22:16,509
you better be looking
like a victim

519
00:22:16,552 --> 00:22:18,032
and not like the
Wicked Witch of the West,

520
00:22:18,075 --> 00:22:20,208
or you're not gonna fire me,
I will quit.

521
00:22:20,251 --> 00:22:22,732
And if I do that, there's not
a law firm in this town

522
00:22:22,776 --> 00:22:25,518
worth a damn that will touch you
with a ten-foot pole.

523
00:22:25,561 --> 00:22:28,259
Second thing.
I am moving heaven and earth

524
00:22:28,303 --> 00:22:30,523
to get down here
and be by your side.

525
00:22:30,566 --> 00:22:33,352
I have every hope
that tomorrow morning

526
00:22:33,395 --> 00:22:35,789
I will be there,
but I can't promise.

527
00:22:35,832 --> 00:22:37,791
What I can promise is that
I am totally involved

528
00:22:37,834 --> 00:22:40,620
in your defense, and those
two men standing behind me

529
00:22:40,663 --> 00:22:42,361
are doing everything
they are supposed to be doing.

530
00:22:42,404 --> 00:22:44,537
But if you're unhappy,
or you have a better idea,

531
00:22:44,580 --> 00:22:47,627
or you have some secret plan
for getting away with murder

532
00:22:47,670 --> 00:22:49,498
on a New York City sidewalk
in broad daylight,

533
00:22:49,542 --> 00:22:50,847
I'd love to hear it.

534
00:22:52,196 --> 00:22:54,373
I didn't think so.

535
00:22:54,416 --> 00:22:57,680
And third, there is one thing
I am certain of.

536
00:22:57,724 --> 00:22:59,290
If we don't put your daughter
on that stand,

537
00:22:59,334 --> 00:23:00,901
you are going to prison.

538
00:23:00,944 --> 00:23:03,947
And the only question will be
for a quarter of a century

539
00:23:03,991 --> 00:23:05,427
or the rest of your life?

540
00:23:05,471 --> 00:23:07,429
She'll never do it.

541
00:23:07,473 --> 00:23:08,952
And I'll never let her.

542
00:23:08,996 --> 00:23:10,824
Then we are all
wasting our time.

543
00:23:10,867 --> 00:23:13,217
No. Not you.

544
00:23:13,261 --> 00:23:14,828
Not yet.

545
00:23:14,871 --> 00:23:18,440
You actually haven't given me
any of your time to waste.

546
00:23:18,484 --> 00:23:20,442
[chuckles]
You guys are right.

547
00:23:20,486 --> 00:23:22,226
She's a peach.
Well, maybe you haven't heard.

548
00:23:22,270 --> 00:23:23,445
I like to win.

549
00:23:23,489 --> 00:23:27,101
So buckle up,
put on a happy face,

550
00:23:27,144 --> 00:23:29,233
and get ready to have
your mind changed.

551
00:23:35,022 --> 00:23:37,416
[indistinct chatter]

552
00:23:47,513 --> 00:23:49,906
You know, if I were advising
that Gorman fella,

553
00:23:49,950 --> 00:23:52,735
I'd tell him to do the, uh,
closing argument himself.

554
00:23:52,779 --> 00:23:55,346
He needs to show that jury that,
even though he doesn't have

555
00:23:55,390 --> 00:23:57,261
a law license,
he's a great litigator.

556
00:23:57,305 --> 00:23:59,481
Would you stop that, please?

557
00:23:59,525 --> 00:24:01,309
We're not supposed
to be doing this.

558
00:24:01,352 --> 00:24:02,658
Jurors are not supposed
to talk to defendants

559
00:24:02,702 --> 00:24:04,312
outside the courtroom.

560
00:24:04,355 --> 00:24:06,401
[elevator bell chimes]

561
00:24:06,445 --> 00:24:08,229
I don't know what
you're talking about.

562
00:24:08,272 --> 00:24:10,492
I didn't say a word.

563
00:24:10,536 --> 00:24:12,407
BENNY: Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury,

564
00:24:12,451 --> 00:24:15,410
I intend to prove to you
that this,

565
00:24:15,454 --> 00:24:17,412
this was no vigilante killing.

566
00:24:17,456 --> 00:24:21,111
That this was an act of
desperation committed by a woman

567
00:24:21,155 --> 00:24:25,594
who fell victim to a mental
condition called EED.

568
00:24:25,638 --> 00:24:27,944
Extreme emotional disturbance.

569
00:24:27,988 --> 00:24:29,424
Objection.

570
00:24:29,468 --> 00:24:31,034
Objection?

571
00:24:32,775 --> 00:24:36,562
Y... Your Honor, I'm still
giving my opening statement.

572
00:24:36,605 --> 00:24:38,302
EED, really, Your Honor?

573
00:24:38,346 --> 00:24:39,739
The State would like
to be heard.

574
00:24:39,782 --> 00:24:42,176
Oh, well, the defense
would like to be heard, too.

575
00:24:42,219 --> 00:24:44,265
As a matter of fact,
the defense would like

576
00:24:44,308 --> 00:24:45,527
to finish
their opening statement.

577
00:24:45,571 --> 00:24:48,225
Wow. We've barely started. Okay.

578
00:24:48,269 --> 00:24:50,750
Want to see you both
in my chambers.

579
00:24:50,793 --> 00:24:53,187
[gallery murmuring]

580
00:24:53,230 --> 00:24:56,756
I love the law.

581
00:24:56,799 --> 00:24:59,846
I know that must sound
ridiculous coming from someone

582
00:24:59,889 --> 00:25:05,329
who's on trial for breaking it,
but it is the truth.

583
00:25:05,373 --> 00:25:08,507
I never planned
on impersonating a-an attorney.

584
00:25:08,550 --> 00:25:12,380
Five years ago,
a woman friend asked me

585
00:25:12,423 --> 00:25:15,818
to go with her to, um,
small claims court,

586
00:25:15,862 --> 00:25:17,428
offer moral support.

587
00:25:17,472 --> 00:25:22,477
Um, I was wearing a suit
'cause, um... [chuckles]

588
00:25:22,521 --> 00:25:25,698
I was a-a mortician
and I had a funeral that day.

589
00:25:25,741 --> 00:25:27,917
And anyway, uh,
the judge started asking

590
00:25:27,961 --> 00:25:29,136
a bunch of questions.

591
00:25:29,179 --> 00:25:30,964
And my friend kind of froze.

592
00:25:31,007 --> 00:25:36,404
So I started answering for her.

593
00:25:36,447 --> 00:25:38,362
[laughs softly]

594
00:25:38,406 --> 00:25:42,105
Next thing I know,
my friend won her case.

595
00:25:42,149 --> 00:25:46,153
And as we, uh,
left the courtroom, this guy

596
00:25:46,196 --> 00:25:49,373
came running up to me
to tell me how impressed he was,

597
00:25:49,417 --> 00:25:50,723
and would I represent him

598
00:25:50,766 --> 00:25:53,726
the following week
i-in traffic court?

599
00:25:53,769 --> 00:25:56,511
One case led to another.

600
00:25:56,555 --> 00:26:01,429
A-And, and the amazing thing
was, I, I never lost.

601
00:26:03,170 --> 00:26:07,217
I also, uh, never charged
more than $35 an hour.

602
00:26:07,261 --> 00:26:09,263
I know that sounds crazy,
but like I said,

603
00:26:09,306 --> 00:26:12,005
I, I love the law.

604
00:26:12,048 --> 00:26:14,094
And thank God for the Internet,

605
00:26:14,137 --> 00:26:17,837
'cause anything I didn't know,
I, I cou-- I could look up.

606
00:26:17,880 --> 00:26:21,057
But of course,
I-I knew it was wrong.

607
00:26:21,101 --> 00:26:24,974
Although I'm not sure
it should be.

608
00:26:25,018 --> 00:26:27,411
I mean, doesn't the law
belong to everyone?

609
00:26:27,455 --> 00:26:31,024
Not just people with money
who can take seven years

610
00:26:31,067 --> 00:26:32,852
off of their lives
and go to school?

611
00:26:32,895 --> 00:26:36,638
Or-or clients who, who can
bankroll a defense?

612
00:26:37,683 --> 00:26:39,293
[clears throat]

613
00:26:39,336 --> 00:26:43,602
But, um, that's a conversation
for another day.

614
00:26:43,645 --> 00:26:44,603
[clears throat]

615
00:26:48,389 --> 00:26:50,391
I'm sorry.

616
00:26:51,697 --> 00:26:53,307
Sorry for what I did,

617
00:26:53,350 --> 00:26:55,526
but I-I would beg you
not to find me guilty.

618
00:26:55,570 --> 00:26:59,487
Because if I'm convicted,
even when I pass the bar,

619
00:26:59,530 --> 00:27:04,927
I will not ever be allowed to
practice my beloved law again.

620
00:27:09,105 --> 00:27:12,892
Also, this will be
the first case I ever lose.

621
00:27:17,723 --> 00:27:19,725
BULL:
Benny!

622
00:27:25,600 --> 00:27:27,558
Terrific.

623
00:27:27,602 --> 00:27:29,430
I'm here.

624
00:27:29,473 --> 00:27:32,955
Oh, it's Benny of Arc.

625
00:27:32,999 --> 00:27:34,174
[groans]

626
00:27:34,217 --> 00:27:35,479
Don't make fun.

627
00:27:35,523 --> 00:27:39,570
My back has declared war
on the rest of my body.

628
00:27:39,614 --> 00:27:41,355
It's all in your head.

629
00:27:41,398 --> 00:27:42,530
Nope. It's all in my back.

630
00:27:42,573 --> 00:27:44,532
[grunts]

631
00:27:44,575 --> 00:27:46,360
Why are you in such a good mood?

632
00:27:46,403 --> 00:27:49,668
I have completed
my service as juror.

633
00:27:49,711 --> 00:27:52,192
The accused was found
not guilty.

634
00:27:52,235 --> 00:27:53,584
Unanimously.

635
00:27:53,628 --> 00:27:55,456
Wow.But the big news is,

636
00:27:55,499 --> 00:27:56,849
I am back on the team.

637
00:27:56,892 --> 00:27:58,502
Ready to head into court

638
00:27:58,546 --> 00:28:00,591
and fight for the freedom
of our delightful client.

639
00:28:00,635 --> 00:28:02,637
Now,

640
00:28:02,681 --> 00:28:05,074
what's making you so anxious
that your back's gone out?

641
00:28:05,118 --> 00:28:07,686
The judge threw out
our EED defense.

642
00:28:07,729 --> 00:28:11,037
Didn't even let me get
through my opening statement.

643
00:28:11,080 --> 00:28:15,302
[sighing]:
Now my back's starting to hurt.

644
00:28:18,392 --> 00:28:21,090
What if we lose?

645
00:28:21,134 --> 00:28:24,790
Remember, we don't have
to change every juror's mind.

646
00:28:24,833 --> 00:28:27,009
Just one will get us a mistrial.

647
00:28:27,053 --> 00:28:29,403
Three or four, and the D.A.
might even dismiss the charges.

648
00:28:29,446 --> 00:28:32,754
When you were a kid, you
believed in Santa, didn't you?

649
00:28:32,798 --> 00:28:34,582
Till I was about 35.

650
00:28:34,625 --> 00:28:36,062
Ah.

651
00:28:37,106 --> 00:28:39,369
You think
what she did was wrong?

652
00:28:39,413 --> 00:28:42,155
Yes.

653
00:28:42,198 --> 00:28:44,418
You think punishing her
for it is right?

654
00:28:44,461 --> 00:28:46,376
No.

655
00:28:46,420 --> 00:28:49,771
Me either.

656
00:28:49,815 --> 00:28:51,773
Benny, we can win this thing.

657
00:28:51,817 --> 00:28:55,168
You have a plan B?

658
00:28:55,211 --> 00:28:58,911
I have a plan B-minus.

659
00:28:58,954 --> 00:29:04,220
It's not great, and it still
presents the same big problem.

660
00:29:04,264 --> 00:29:06,092
Okay. Lay it on me.

661
00:29:06,135 --> 00:29:09,443
We go in there tomorrow and
announce a new defense theory.

662
00:29:09,486 --> 00:29:11,662
It's called defense of others.

663
00:29:11,706 --> 00:29:12,794
Ah.

664
00:29:12,838 --> 00:29:15,101
Defense of others.
I know it well.

665
00:29:15,144 --> 00:29:18,408
It's kind of like self-defense,
only we argue that

666
00:29:18,452 --> 00:29:21,629
Heather shot that man in order
to protect her daughter.

667
00:29:21,672 --> 00:29:25,546
Which I believe with all
my heart is the truth.

668
00:29:25,589 --> 00:29:27,766
Just can't figure out
how to prove it.

669
00:29:27,809 --> 00:29:31,465
[grunting]:
Great. The pain is back.

670
00:29:31,508 --> 00:29:33,510
[exhales]

671
00:29:39,516 --> 00:29:41,431
Who did you say it was?

672
00:29:41,475 --> 00:29:42,955
AUNT:
A friend of your mom's.

673
00:29:44,565 --> 00:29:46,523
Hello?

674
00:29:46,567 --> 00:29:48,525
Penny Spiro.

675
00:29:48,569 --> 00:29:51,267
I'm Dr. Jason Bull.

676
00:29:51,311 --> 00:29:52,703
Sorry to show up
on your doorstep

677
00:29:52,747 --> 00:29:54,488
so early in the morning,
but I'm part

678
00:29:54,531 --> 00:29:56,403
of your mom's
legal team,

679
00:29:56,446 --> 00:29:58,405
and I desperately need you
to do two things I've been told

680
00:29:58,448 --> 00:29:59,841
you're not gonna want to do.

681
00:29:59,885 --> 00:30:01,843
I won't testify.

682
00:30:01,887 --> 00:30:04,498
That's only the first one.

683
00:30:04,541 --> 00:30:08,981
I also need you to convince
your mom to let you do it.

684
00:30:09,024 --> 00:30:11,244
It's a pretty simple system.
Uh, four cameras.

685
00:30:11,287 --> 00:30:12,636
Three inside the store.

686
00:30:12,680 --> 00:30:14,203
One that focuses
on the cash register

687
00:30:14,247 --> 00:30:15,857
and the customers as they pay.

688
00:30:15,901 --> 00:30:18,425
Two that show customers walking
through the aisles of the store

689
00:30:18,468 --> 00:30:20,296
from opposite sides
of the store.

690
00:30:20,340 --> 00:30:22,864
And a wireless camera,
mounted without permission

691
00:30:22,908 --> 00:30:25,345
on the lamp post outside
the store, presumably,

692
00:30:25,388 --> 00:30:27,956
to capture people coming
into and out of the store,

693
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:29,871
specifically those
who haven't paid.

694
00:30:29,915 --> 00:30:31,699
Shoplifters, that kind of thing.

695
00:30:31,742 --> 00:30:35,877
And when you examined the DVR,
what did you discover?

696
00:30:35,921 --> 00:30:38,532
I discovered that
on four consecutive days,

697
00:30:38,575 --> 00:30:40,403
beginning with June 11,

698
00:30:40,447 --> 00:30:43,667
the defendant planted herself
outside the store.

699
00:30:43,711 --> 00:30:45,974
Twice in her car,
twice on foot.

700
00:30:46,018 --> 00:30:48,237
And in your
professional opinion,

701
00:30:48,281 --> 00:30:50,022
what was she doing?BENNY:
Objection, Your Honor.

702
00:30:50,065 --> 00:30:52,546
The assistant district attorney
is asking

703
00:30:52,589 --> 00:30:53,764
the witness to speculate.

704
00:30:53,808 --> 00:30:55,723
She's asking
a professional investigator

705
00:30:55,766 --> 00:30:57,377
to give her expert opinion

706
00:30:57,420 --> 00:30:59,379
based on the evidence
in front of her.

707
00:30:59,422 --> 00:31:00,859
Overruled.

708
00:31:00,902 --> 00:31:02,991
You may answer the question.

709
00:31:03,035 --> 00:31:05,472
Waiting. She's waiting.

710
00:31:05,515 --> 00:31:06,516
Waiting.

711
00:31:06,560 --> 00:31:08,562
Any idea for what?

712
00:31:08,605 --> 00:31:10,520
Well, I think
that became apparent

713
00:31:10,564 --> 00:31:14,002
on the fifth day,
when she executed Mr. Briggs.

714
00:31:14,046 --> 00:31:15,482
WAKEFIELD:
The prosecution has no further
questions for this witness.

715
00:31:15,525 --> 00:31:18,093
I need to hear
something positive.

716
00:31:18,137 --> 00:31:21,575
Well, this jury
is positively unanimous.

717
00:31:21,618 --> 00:31:23,229
Defense will cross-examine this
witness after the lunch break.

718
00:31:23,272 --> 00:31:25,318
Court is in recess.[gavel bangs]

719
00:31:25,361 --> 00:31:27,363
Thank God.

720
00:31:28,451 --> 00:31:30,540
Nice of you to join us.

721
00:31:30,584 --> 00:31:32,586
Ah. I thought so, too.

722
00:31:37,896 --> 00:31:40,550
Oh, my God. Penny.

723
00:31:43,989 --> 00:31:46,252
Oh...

724
00:31:46,295 --> 00:31:50,386
I told Dr. Bull everything.

725
00:31:53,259 --> 00:31:56,479
That I'm the reason
all this happened.

726
00:31:57,437 --> 00:32:01,441
And I want to take the stand.

727
00:32:01,484 --> 00:32:02,746
BENNY:
Penny...

728
00:32:02,790 --> 00:32:07,099
could you please tell
the jury about the day

729
00:32:07,142 --> 00:32:10,015
they found Ella and caught
the man who killed her?

730
00:32:11,538 --> 00:32:16,978
Well... it was
the worst day of my life.

731
00:32:17,022 --> 00:32:19,763
[laughing nervously]:
And also,

732
00:32:19,807 --> 00:32:22,984
weirdly, kind of the best.

733
00:32:23,028 --> 00:32:24,855
How do you mean?

734
00:32:24,899 --> 00:32:27,075
PENNY:
Well, uh,

735
00:32:27,119 --> 00:32:31,514
it was horrible because it...

736
00:32:31,558 --> 00:32:35,605
it was the moment I absolutely
knew my sister was gone.

737
00:32:35,649 --> 00:32:38,608
Uh...

738
00:32:38,652 --> 00:32:40,654
There was no denying it.

739
00:32:40,697 --> 00:32:44,310
She was never coming back.

740
00:32:47,052 --> 00:32:50,011
But later that night, um,

741
00:32:50,055 --> 00:32:54,363
it finally started to sink in
that they caught him,

742
00:32:54,407 --> 00:32:55,930
the guy who did it.

743
00:32:55,974 --> 00:32:58,889
They had him,
and he was going

744
00:32:58,933 --> 00:33:01,936
to prison forever.

745
00:33:04,547 --> 00:33:10,031
I remember my mother holding me

746
00:33:10,075 --> 00:33:15,036
and telling me...
it was going to be okay.

747
00:33:17,082 --> 00:33:20,346
That it-it may never go back
to the way it was.

748
00:33:22,391 --> 00:33:27,092
But it would go back
to a new normal.

749
00:33:27,135 --> 00:33:29,485
I could live my life again.

750
00:33:29,529 --> 00:33:33,054
I could leave my house.

751
00:33:33,098 --> 00:33:36,362
I-I could go to school,
see my, see my friends.

752
00:33:36,405 --> 00:33:39,669
In a couple of years,
go to college.

753
00:33:39,713 --> 00:33:41,889
Have a future.

754
00:33:42,933 --> 00:33:45,849
We were safe.

755
00:33:45,893 --> 00:33:48,504
BENNY:
And then?

756
00:33:50,115 --> 00:33:54,554
And then they let him
out of jail.

757
00:33:54,597 --> 00:33:56,860
And I realized

758
00:33:56,904 --> 00:33:59,863
there was never
gonna be a normal.

759
00:33:59,907 --> 00:34:02,953
And what did that feel like?

760
00:34:03,998 --> 00:34:06,044
We were terrified.

761
00:34:06,087 --> 00:34:08,307
I was terrified.

762
00:34:08,350 --> 00:34:12,398
My mom had to drive me
to and from school again.

763
00:34:12,441 --> 00:34:15,966
And, uh,
when we got home,

764
00:34:16,010 --> 00:34:18,534
we'd lock the doors
and check the windows.

765
00:34:18,578 --> 00:34:23,539
And... I didn't see my friends.

766
00:34:23,583 --> 00:34:25,976
I didn't play soccer.

767
00:34:26,020 --> 00:34:27,935
I dropped out of chorus.

768
00:34:27,978 --> 00:34:29,110
And it just

769
00:34:29,154 --> 00:34:31,460
went on like this?

770
00:34:31,504 --> 00:34:34,072
F-For a few months.

771
00:34:34,115 --> 00:34:38,424
So I went to my mom and
I told her that if I couldn't

772
00:34:38,467 --> 00:34:44,038
live a normal life,
that I was going to kill myself.

773
00:34:46,301 --> 00:34:49,609
BENNY: And what was
her reaction to that?

774
00:34:49,652 --> 00:34:50,784
PENNY:
We started experimenting.

775
00:34:50,827 --> 00:34:56,181
I-I'd go out for, like, an hour.

776
00:34:56,224 --> 00:35:00,446
Or I'd walk home from school
with a friend.

777
00:35:00,489 --> 00:35:04,667
I knew those must have been
the longest hours for my mother,

778
00:35:04,711 --> 00:35:07,975
but I started
to feel alive again.

779
00:35:08,018 --> 00:35:10,717
BENNY:
And...

780
00:35:10,760 --> 00:35:13,328
what happened on June 10?

781
00:35:13,372 --> 00:35:16,723
I was walking home from school
and I felt like a soda,

782
00:35:16,766 --> 00:35:18,725
so I stopped at the bodega.

783
00:35:18,768 --> 00:35:20,161
By yourself?

784
00:35:20,205 --> 00:35:21,858
Uh, by myself.

785
00:35:21,902 --> 00:35:25,123
And, um, I went
to the refrigerator case

786
00:35:25,166 --> 00:35:29,344
and I grabbed a can

787
00:35:29,388 --> 00:35:33,696
and I turned around
and he was standing there.

788
00:35:33,740 --> 00:35:34,871
Mr. Briggs?

789
00:35:34,915 --> 00:35:36,090
Mm-hmm.

790
00:35:36,134 --> 00:35:38,397
And did he say anything to you?

791
00:35:38,440 --> 00:35:41,748
No. He was just staring at me.

792
00:35:41,791 --> 00:35:44,142
Did he touch you?

793
00:35:44,185 --> 00:35:45,752
Try to reach
out to you?

794
00:35:45,795 --> 00:35:46,709
No.

795
00:35:46,753 --> 00:35:49,408
And what did you do?

796
00:35:49,451 --> 00:35:52,193
I put the can down
and I ran out of there.

797
00:35:52,237 --> 00:35:53,847
Did you go home?

798
00:35:53,890 --> 00:35:57,894
No. I-I went to the coffee shop
next door and I called my mom.

799
00:35:57,938 --> 00:36:00,854
And she came
and picked me up.

800
00:36:00,897 --> 00:36:02,029
BENNY:
That was on June 10,

801
00:36:02,072 --> 00:36:03,813
and on June 11 your mom began

802
00:36:03,857 --> 00:36:05,554
looking for Mr. Briggs
at the bodega.

803
00:36:05,598 --> 00:36:06,860
WAKEFIELD:
Objection.

804
00:36:06,903 --> 00:36:09,036
That's not a question.
Counsel is testifying.

805
00:36:09,079 --> 00:36:10,690
I apologize, Your Honor.

806
00:36:10,733 --> 00:36:13,214
I just have one more question.

807
00:36:13,258 --> 00:36:15,260
The last time

808
00:36:15,303 --> 00:36:20,221
you were in court, during your
little sister's murder trial,

809
00:36:20,265 --> 00:36:21,657
you were on the stand,

810
00:36:21,701 --> 00:36:24,660
and there was something
that A.D.A. Wakefield

811
00:36:24,704 --> 00:36:30,318
wouldn't allow you to say
that was important to you.

812
00:36:30,362 --> 00:36:32,015
You want to say it now?

813
00:36:32,059 --> 00:36:33,234
Your Honor.

814
00:36:33,278 --> 00:36:35,410
Sit down, Ms. Wakefield.

815
00:36:36,846 --> 00:36:40,894
I just wanted to tell the court

816
00:36:40,937 --> 00:36:44,245
that I heard his voice.

817
00:36:44,289 --> 00:36:47,248
When he broke in
that night

818
00:36:47,292 --> 00:36:51,731
and covered my head and put me
in the closet, he spoke to me,

819
00:36:51,774 --> 00:36:55,735
and I knew instantly

820
00:36:55,778 --> 00:36:57,780
who it was.

821
00:36:59,826 --> 00:37:01,828
We all knew who it was.

822
00:37:04,657 --> 00:37:06,746
Why did you let him out?

823
00:37:09,052 --> 00:37:13,753
The defense rests, Your Honor.

824
00:37:13,796 --> 00:37:18,410
I can't explain it,
but nothing is moving here.

825
00:37:22,849 --> 00:37:24,807
[elevator bell chimes]

826
00:37:30,770 --> 00:37:31,814
CABLE'S VOICE:
Hey, Dr. Bull.

827
00:37:31,858 --> 00:37:33,860
Hey, Cable.

828
00:37:44,523 --> 00:37:46,264
Uh...

829
00:37:46,307 --> 00:37:49,441
Uh, yeah, I just put
everything right over there.

830
00:37:49,484 --> 00:37:51,486
[sighs]
Thank you.

831
00:37:55,316 --> 00:37:57,536
Gabriel.

832
00:37:57,579 --> 00:37:59,102
Excuse me?

833
00:37:59,146 --> 00:38:01,888
My name. My name is Gabriel.

834
00:38:01,931 --> 00:38:04,717
Okay.

835
00:38:04,760 --> 00:38:08,155
But yours can't
seriously be Danny, right?

836
00:38:08,198 --> 00:38:10,331
Danielle.

837
00:38:10,375 --> 00:38:12,986
Ah, you see, well,
that makes more sense.

838
00:38:13,029 --> 00:38:14,944
Listen, can you tell

839
00:38:14,988 --> 00:38:18,644
your-your friend's family that
I-I need to clean the place out?

840
00:38:18,687 --> 00:38:20,646
It's just, the landlord wants

841
00:38:20,689 --> 00:38:23,866
to put the apartment
back on the market.

842
00:38:23,910 --> 00:38:26,739
Yeah, I'll-I'll
let 'em know.

843
00:38:29,829 --> 00:38:33,615
I would like to go
to the funeral.

844
00:38:33,659 --> 00:38:36,923
Or the memorial, whatever
it is that they're having.

845
00:38:36,966 --> 00:38:38,533
You know.

846
00:38:38,577 --> 00:38:41,144
Okay.

847
00:38:41,188 --> 00:38:42,624
[clears throat]

848
00:38:42,668 --> 00:38:43,843
I'll-I'll find you, I'll, um,

849
00:38:43,886 --> 00:38:47,194
I'll let you know
when I-I hear something.

850
00:38:47,237 --> 00:38:48,717
[phone ringing]Thank you.

851
00:38:48,761 --> 00:38:50,589
No, please.

852
00:38:50,632 --> 00:38:51,894
Excuse me.

853
00:38:51,938 --> 00:38:53,592
Hello.

854
00:38:53,635 --> 00:38:57,378
Oh, my God. Uh, yeah.

855
00:38:57,422 --> 00:38:59,162
Work, um...

856
00:38:59,206 --> 00:39:01,339
A jury we've been waiting for
just came in.

857
00:39:01,382 --> 00:39:02,731
Thanks again for your help.

858
00:39:02,775 --> 00:39:03,906
Ah.

859
00:39:03,950 --> 00:39:06,082
[chuckles]
Sorry.

860
00:39:08,084 --> 00:39:11,000
Thank you.

861
00:39:11,044 --> 00:39:15,483
It seems in the matter
of The State v. Heather Spiro,

862
00:39:15,527 --> 00:39:18,704
our jury is hopelessly
deadlocked.

863
00:39:18,747 --> 00:39:20,836
I say "hopelessly" because,
according to this note,

864
00:39:20,880 --> 00:39:24,623
while six of our jurors
find the defendant guilty,

865
00:39:24,666 --> 00:39:27,582
six believe her to be innocent.

866
00:39:27,626 --> 00:39:31,673
I see no other choice
but to declare a mistrial.

867
00:39:31,717 --> 00:39:35,068
Would the prosecutor like to
schedule a date for a retrial?

868
00:39:45,470 --> 00:39:48,168
I believe, in their inability
to send a unified verdict,

869
00:39:48,211 --> 00:39:51,476
our jurors are sending
an important message.

870
00:39:51,519 --> 00:39:54,653
Perhaps because of all
these months served behind bars,

871
00:39:54,696 --> 00:39:57,525
perhaps in the loss of a child,

872
00:39:57,569 --> 00:39:59,484
justice has
already been served.

873
00:39:59,527 --> 00:40:01,094
The State
no longer believes

874
00:40:01,137 --> 00:40:03,575
this woman is a threat to
society, and with that in mind,

875
00:40:03,618 --> 00:40:06,795
in the interest of justice,
we move to dismiss all charges.

876
00:40:06,839 --> 00:40:08,797
♪

877
00:40:37,391 --> 00:40:39,393
[elevator bell chimes]

878
00:40:47,619 --> 00:40:49,621
[indistinct chatter]

879
00:41:05,201 --> 00:41:07,726
Can I help you? You
look a little lost.

880
00:41:07,769 --> 00:41:09,075
I'm sorry, uh,

881
00:41:09,118 --> 00:41:11,686
my name is Ellen McCrory.

882
00:41:11,730 --> 00:41:13,253
My daughter used to work here.

883
00:41:13,296 --> 00:41:15,734
I'm just here to pick up
some of her things.

884
00:41:15,777 --> 00:41:19,520
Boy, this is
so not what I pictured.

885
00:41:19,564 --> 00:41:22,131
Mrs. McCrory.

886
00:41:22,175 --> 00:41:23,829
Cable's mother.

887
00:41:25,483 --> 00:41:27,136
I'm so sorry.

888
00:41:28,486 --> 00:41:31,445
I'm Jason Bull.
Your daughter worked for me.

889
00:41:31,489 --> 00:41:33,969
Oh, my. You...

890
00:41:34,013 --> 00:41:35,144
You're him.

891
00:41:35,188 --> 00:41:36,929
Hmm.

892
00:41:36,972 --> 00:41:39,105
Well, she, uh,
she talked about you a lot.

893
00:41:39,148 --> 00:41:41,977
Ah. Lies. Nothing but lies.

894
00:41:45,067 --> 00:41:46,504
I miss her...

895
00:41:50,116 --> 00:41:51,987
Stay right here. I'll get
somebody to help you.

896
00:41:52,031 --> 00:41:54,033
Okay, thank you.

897
00:42:08,177 --> 00:42:10,179
[exhales]

898
00:42:13,879 --> 00:42:16,446
Marissa, do me a favor.

899
00:42:16,490 --> 00:42:20,059
Cable's mom is in the War Room,

900
00:42:20,102 --> 00:42:24,367
and she's looking
a little lost, so...

901
00:42:24,411 --> 00:42:26,369
Exactly.

902
00:42:26,413 --> 00:42:28,241
Appreciate it.

903
